T1  - Discriminating between autoregressive forms: A Monte Carlo comparison of Bayesian and ad hoc methods
AU  - Giles, D.E.A.
JO  - Journal of Econometrics
VL  - 3
IS  - 3
SP  - 229
EP  - 248
PY  - 1975
DA  - 1975/08/01/
SN  - 0304-4076
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-4076(75)90033-0
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304407675900330
AB  - The paper considers the problem of discriminating between the autoregressive forms of a Koyck distributed lag model and a regression model with autocorrelated distrubances. Several interpretations of an ad hoc rule-of-thumb suggested by Griliches are compared with Bayesian posterior odds analysis in a Monte Carlo experiment. The Bayesian analysis is generally superior to the rules-of-thumb, the latter exhibiting large probabilities of type I error, and low power. The rules-of-thumb excessively favour the distributed lag model, while the Bayesian method is free from such bias. All methods improve with increased sample size.
ER  - 
